description: Borrowed from Middle French magasin (“warehouse, store”), from Italian magazzino (“storehouse”), ultimately from Arabic مَخَازِن‎ pl (maḵāzin), plural of مَخْزَن‎ (maḵzan, “storeroom, storehouse”), noun of place from خَزَنَ‎ (ḵazana, “to store, to stock, to lay up”).

entries.meaning: A non-academic periodical publication, generally consisting of sheets of paper folded in half and stapled at the fold.
(nautical) The portion of a warship where munitions are stored.
examples: The cruiser blew up when a shell hit its magazine.

entries.meaning: A chamber in or attachable to a firearm enabling multiple rounds of ammunition to be fed into the firearm.
A reservoir or supply chamber for a stove, battery, camera, typesetting machine, or other apparatus.
(archaic) A country or district especially rich in natural products.
(archaic) A city viewed as a marketing center.
(archaic) A store, or shop, where goods are kept for sale.
(television, UK, Ireland) A collection of Teletext pages.
examples: Most teletext "magazines" contain about 100 pages of information, typically including news headlines, weather reports, sports scores, video games, and stock prices.
